id: volnix-app-public-memory-engine
title: VolnixApp.memory property + enable_memory() helper
scope: feature
owners: [@TODO]
paths:
  - volnix/app.py
  - tests/integration/test_app_memory_engine.py
surfaces:
  - VolnixApp.memory (new public @property)
  - VolnixApp.enable_memory (new public async helper)
dependencies: [workflow, volnix-app-public-llm-router]

intent:
  ``MemoryEngine`` (the 11th engine, the one that gives NPCs
  episodic recall + persona drift) is currently only constructed
  inside ``configure_agency()`` and only when
  ``config.memory.enabled=True``. Library consumers who want
  memory WITHOUT spinning up the full agency stack (Rehearse's
  persona moat, cassette-replay-with-memory tests, any product
  that wants character continuity without the agency engine's
  activation lifecycle) have no way in.

  This TNL adds two surfaces:

  1. ``VolnixApp.memory`` — a public ``@property`` returning the
     constructed ``MemoryEngine`` (or ``None`` before
     construction). Symmetric with every other engine accessor.

  2. ``VolnixApp.enable_memory(world_seed: int)`` — an async
     helper that explicitly constructs the memory engine without
     requiring ``configure_agency``. The helper IS the explicit
     opt-in: it bypasses the ``config.memory.enabled`` toggle
     (which only governs the auto-construction path inside
     ``configure_agency``).

  After ``enable_memory(...)`` returns, ``app.memory`` is the
  constructed engine. If ``configure_agency()`` runs later, it
  detects the existing engine and skips reconstruction (idempotent).

behaviors:
  # Property
  - ``VolnixApp`` MUST expose ``memory`` as a ``@property``.
    Class-level descriptor MUST be ``isinstance(..., property)``.
  - The property MUST return the same instance internal callers
    see at ``self._memory_engine``. Identity holds:
    ``app.memory is app._memory_engine``.
  - Pre-construction access (before ``enable_memory`` OR
    ``configure_agency`` has wired memory) MUST NOT raise; returns
    ``None``. Same convention as every other public engine
    accessor.
  - Return-type annotation MUST be ``MemoryEngine | None`` (memory
    is optional unlike the always-present session_manager / bus /
    ledger).
  - The property MUST be additive — ``self._memory_engine``
    remains accessible. Existing internal reads
    (``configure_agency`` line ~1729, ``stop()`` line ~652) MUST
    continue to work unchanged.

  # enable_memory helper
  - ``VolnixApp`` MUST gain an async method
    ``enable_memory(self, world_seed: int) -> MemoryEngine``.
  - The helper MUST raise ``RuntimeError`` if called before
    ``start()`` has wired the LLM router (i.e.,
    ``self._llm_router is None``). MemoryEngine's Consolidator
    requires the router; failing fast beats a confusing downstream
    crash. Error message MUST instruct the caller to call
    ``await app.start()`` first.
  - The helper MUST raise ``RuntimeError`` if called before the
    connection manager is initialised (i.e., ``self._conn_mgr is
    None``). Same fast-fail rationale.
  - The helper MUST construct the engine via the same code path
    ``configure_agency`` uses (``build_memory_engine`` from
    ``volnix.registry.composition``), passing ``memory_config``,
    ``world_seed``, ``llm_router=self._llm_router``,
    ``connection_manager=self._conn_mgr``.
  - The helper MUST construct the engine even when
    ``self._config.memory.enabled is False``. The helper is the
    explicit opt-in — config is bypassed by passing a copy with
    ``enabled=True`` (``self._config.memory.model_copy(update={"enabled": True})``).
    Rationale: callers shouldn't have to flip TWO knobs.
  - After construction, the helper MUST run the same
    initialisation sequence ``configure_agency`` runs:
    1. attach the ledger (``engine._ledger = self._ledger``)
    2. ``await engine.initialize({}, self._bus)``
    3. ``await engine.start()``
    4. stash on ``self._memory_engine``
  - The helper MUST be idempotent w.r.t. ``world_seed``: when
    called a second time with the SAME ``world_seed`` and the
    engine is already constructed, return the existing engine
    (no reconstruction). When called a second time with a
    DIFFERENT ``world_seed``, raise ``RuntimeError`` (memory is
    seeded to a single world; reseeding mid-run is a wiring bug).
  - The helper MUST return the constructed (or already-existing)
    ``MemoryEngine`` instance. Return type is ``MemoryEngine``,
    not ``MemoryEngine | None`` — if construction fails for any
    reason the helper raises, never returns ``None``.

  # configure_agency interaction (idempotence)
  - When ``configure_agency`` runs and detects
    ``self._memory_engine is not None`` (because ``enable_memory``
    ran first), it MUST skip the construction block and proceed
    directly to the agency-injection step
    (``agency.set_memory_engine(self._memory_engine)``). No
    duplicate-construction, no error.
  - When ``configure_agency`` runs first (existing path), then
    ``enable_memory`` is called later, the helper detects
    ``self._memory_engine is not None`` with a matching seed (or
    no recorded seed yet) and returns the existing engine.

  # Test coverage in tests/integration/test_app_memory_engine.py
  - ``test_positive_memory_property_exists_on_class``
  - ``test_negative_memory_property_returns_none_before_construction``
  - ``test_positive_enable_memory_constructs_engine`` — happy path
  - ``test_negative_enable_memory_before_start_raises`` — guard
    fires when ``_llm_router`` is None
  - ``test_positive_enable_memory_bypasses_config_memory_enabled``
    — works even with ``config.memory.enabled=False``
  - ``test_positive_enable_memory_idempotent_same_seed``
  - ``test_negative_enable_memory_different_seed_raises``
  - ``test_positive_property_returns_engine_after_enable_memory``
    — ``app.memory is app._memory_engine`` after ``enable_memory``
  - ``test_positive_configure_agency_after_enable_memory_skips_construction``
    — agency injection still happens; no duplicate
    ``build_memory_engine`` call (assert via spy / call count)
  - ``test_positive_underscore_attribute_remains_accessible``

non-goals:
  - No refactor of ``configure_agency``'s memory-construction
    block beyond the idempotence guard. Extracting a shared
    private helper (``_construct_memory_engine``) is reasonable
    if it keeps both paths in sync, but is an implementation
    detail — the public surface is what this TNL locks.
  - No public re-export of ``MemoryEngine`` from
    ``volnix.__init__`` in this TNL. The class is reachable via
    ``app.memory`` instances; consumers type-hint with
    ``volnix.engines.memory.MemoryEngine`` if needed. Public
    re-export is a separate decision (touches semver pin
    surface).
  - No persistence of "which seed was enable_memory called with"
    in any storage layer. The seed match is in-process only via
    the constructed engine's state.
  - No support for multiple MemoryEngine instances per app.
    ``enable_memory`` is a single-engine accessor; multi-world
    apps are out of scope.
  - No CLI surface change.
  - No changes to ``MemoryEngine`` itself.

rationale:
  Mirrors Rehearse gap 1 (``session_manager``) for the property
  half. The helper half is the new piece: it lifts the
  construction trigger out of ``configure_agency`` so consumers
  can opt into memory without opting into agency. The
  ``config.memory.enabled`` bypass is the opinionated call —
  one knob, not two. Keeping ``configure_agency``'s auto-path
  unchanged means existing apps that toggle config keep working
  byte-identically; the new path is purely additive.

  Idempotence both directions (``enable_memory`` then
  ``configure_agency``, OR vice versa) means the order doesn't
  matter and consumers can mix the two without surprise. The
  seed-mismatch guard catches the "two worlds in one app" wiring
  bug at the earliest possible point.
